:::: {#box-1 .callout-note .species title="Box 1. Taxonomic advances since the 2018 National Biodiversity Assessment" collapse="true"}
The latest Red List assessment for freshwater fishes of South Africa was done in 2016/17. These findings were integrated into the National Biodiversity Assessment 2018. Key outcomes of this assessment were the identification of substantial taxonomic gaps across several species, and the lack of ongoing monitoring and uncertainties about species distribution patterns; highlighting the need for targeted research. In response, several research initiatives, primarily led by NRF-SAIAB in collaboration with SANBI and other partners, were launched to advance taxonomic understanding and fill sampling gaps. These include the Topotypes Project (NRF FBIP), the Karoo BioGaps Project (NRF FBIP), the [Waterberg Biodiversity Project](https://fbip.co.za/news/waterberg-biodiversity-project-reminds-us-what-programme-is-about/) (NRF FBIP), the [Tilapia Mapping Project](https://saiab.ac.za/study-underway-to-determine-spread-of-invasive-alien-nile-tilapia-a-major-threat-to-south-africas-biodiversity/) (DFFE & SANBI), the [REFRESH Project](https://saiab.ac.za/platforms/fresh-water-field-unit/refresh-project/) (NRF FBIP) and the eDNA Project (WRC) that were initiated to fill the identified taxonomic and species distribution gaps.

These projects, some of which are still ongoing, have already yielded significant scientific breakthroughs: 28 new fish species have been formally described, 11 previously synonymised species have been revalidated, and several candidate species requiring further taxonomic investigation have been uncovered across southern Africa [@sithole2024a; @sithole2023a; @mutizwa2025a; @skelton2024a; @chakona2022a; @fricke2025a]. Major milestones for South African species include comprehensive genetic assessments and taxonomic revisions of the genera *Pseudobarbus*, *Galaxias*, *Enteromius*, *Labeo*, *Labeobarbus*, *Anoplopterus*, *Sandelia* and *Glossogobius*, which have collectively increased the number of freshwater fish species in the country from 105 in 2016 to 139 in 2025 [@chakona2017a; @chakona2020a; @bronaugh2020a; @mazungula2021a; @kambikambi2021a; @zarei2025a; @zarei2025b; @zarei2025c; @ramoejane2025a; @scheepers2025b; @scheepers2024b; @skelton2024a]. Several additional new species are in the process of being formally described for inclusion into the 2027 reassessment.

Strategic research initiatives have significantly strengthened the evidence base for conservation planning in South Africa. The REFRESH project addressed critical sampling gaps and updated historical records for inclusion into future Red List assessments. The Waterberg Biodiversity Project expanded species occurrence data in a priority region and highlighted the role of existing terrestrial conservation areas in safeguarding the region’s unique ichthyofauna from escalating anthropogenic pressures [@d2025a]. In parallel, NRF-SAIAB is advancing the use of environmental DNA (eDNA) as a tool for long-term monitoring of freshwater fishes of conservation and socio-economic importance. However, the reliability of eDNA-based assessments depends on an accurate and resolved taxonomic framework. Continued efforts to address taxonomic uncertainty and uncover undocumented diversity, particularly for the Amatola-Winterberg, Southern Temperate and Zambezian Lowveld freshwater ecoregions of South Africa, remain essential as this has direct implications for future Red List Assessments and the broader conservation agenda.

